info.description: An attacker empties the chosen memory section by filling it with zeroes.

An attacker performs this step several times to gather a large enough dataset to perform statistical analysis on the times it took to read the bytes for each flush and reload operation. An attacker is then able to determin the section of RAM stored in the cache that contains the secret information by determining the quickest time, in comparison with the other times.
An attacker reads one byte of the copied data and records how long it takes to read the byte.

An attacker performs a series of flush and reload operations to have the selected memory section copied with some stored data. This will also incur a race condition which will cause the CPU to load the associated memory sections into the Cache.
An attacker selects a block of memory that they control and hasn't been cached before.

Before the CPU is able to determine that the function should not be executed and removes the cached sensitive variable, an attacker would retrieve the information from the cache and be able to read it.

Execute the identified vulnerable function several times such that the CPU's branch predictor will think the next loop also satisfies the loop condition and temporarily store the contents of the sensitive variable in the cache.
An attacker is able to reverse engineer a specific program that contains sensitive information and checks functions where sensitive variables are stored in RAM.

Spectre is an attack that induces a CPU to speculatively perform operations that would not occur during strictly serialized in-order processing of the programâ€™s instructions, which in turn would leak confidential information stored in RAM via a covert channel to the adversary.

Meltdown exploits a race condition in CPUs between memory access and privilege level checking while an instruction is being processed. In conjunction with a CPU cache side-channel attack, privilege level checks can be bypassed, allowing access to memory used by an operating system, or other running processes.

An attacker could possibly exploit the out-of-order execution, speculative execution, or caching mechanisms of the CPU to retrieve data stored in RAM that would otherwise be restricted from access under normal usage of the device that the CPU is integrated in.
An attacker is able to reverse engineer a specific program that contains sensitive information and checks functions where sensitive variables are accessed under specific conditions (an if statement).
